TIGER_HTML = '<img src="{}" width="400" height="200" />'.format(SVG_TIGER_URL)

TIGER_OUTPUT = '/tmp/tiger.png'

Creating an Ichabod client¶

An ichabod client can be constructed with no arguments. Below we construct it with a port and a timeout, since ours is not running on the default port, and we it timeout quickly if necessary.

In [65]:
client = ichabod.IchabodClient(port=9191, timeout=5)

Hello, world!¶

The client provides three rasterization methods: rasterize, which accepts an html or url argument, as well as rasterize_html and rasterize_url, which only accept each arugment respectively. The only two required arguments are html or url and width, which gives our browser a width.

In [66]:
result = client.rasterize(html='<h2>Hello, world!</h2>', width=300)

Image(filename=result['path'])
Out[66]:

Performance¶

Ichabod is built to render and return a repsonse quickly. Below we can use the IPython %%timeit magic to see just how fast our example renders. In this case, it takes just under 7 ms per run.

In [67]:
%%timeit
client.rasterize(html='<h1>Hello, world!</h1>', width=300)

100 loops, best of 3: 6.9 ms per loop

Here's a more complex example: the classic SVG tiger.

In [68]:
%%timeit
client.rasterize(
    output=TIGER_OUTPUT,
    html=TIGER_HTML,
    width=400)

10 loops, best of 3: 23.5 ms per loop
In [69]:
Image(filename='/tmp/tiger.png')
Out[69]:

Comparable technologies¶

Since we're using the classic SVG tiger, we can compare our timing metrics to the example in the phantomjs documentation.

PLEASE NOTE: this is not an apples-to-apples comparison, since it includes the time it takes to start the phantomjs runtime. In our testing, ichabod is still roughly an order of magnitude faster at rendering, but perhaps not 20x faster, if we profile just the rendering.

In [101]:
%%timeit -n 10
!phantomjs /usr/share/phantomjs/examples/rasterize.js http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/f/fd/Ghostscript_Tiger.svg /tmp/tiger.png

10 loops, best of 3: 590 ms per loop

Rendering webpages by URL¶

We can also pass the url keyword argument to render a remote resource.

In [76]:
result = client.rasterize_url(url='http://example.com', width=1000, height=500)
In [77]:
Image(filename=result['path'])
Out[77]:

Evaluating JS¶

We can pass JavaScript code with the js parameter which is evaluated in the page context and returned in the resulting JSON in the result key. Given that we're communicating with a relatively fast page, this should return quickly as well.

In [97]:
print client.evaluate(
    js='(function() { return JSON.stringify(document.characterSet); })()',
    url='http://example.com')['result']

UTF-8
In [98]:
%%timeit
client.evaluate(
    js='(function() { return JSON.stringify(document.characterSet); })()',
    url='http://example.com')

100 loops, best of 3: 9.9 ms per loop

Animations and the ichabod JS API¶

Ichabod exposes an API which scripts in the js parameter can use to control when the page is rasterized, and to create complex animations.

In [266]:
ANIMATION_HTML = """
<html>
<head>
    <style>
        body {background: transparent;}
        #matrix {color: green; width: 390; overflow: auto; font-family: monospace}
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <div id="matrix">LOADING ...</div>
</body>
</html>
"""

ANIMATION_JS = """
(function() {
    ichabod.setTransparent(1);
    ichabod.setLooping(1);
    var matrix = document.getElementById('matrix');
    for (var i = 1; i < 100; i++) {
        var codez = [];
        for (var j = 1; j < 666; j++) {
            codez.push(Math.random() < 0.5 ? 0 : 1);
        }
        matrix.innerText = codez.join(' ');
        ichabod.snapshotPage(10);
    }
    ichabod.saveToOutput();
})()
"""

# HACK! IPython notebook doesn't want to show a .gif file.
ANIMATION_OUTPUT = '/tmp/example-anim.png'

animation_result = client.evaluate(
    format='gif',
    html=ANIMATION_HTML,
    output=ANIMATION_OUTPUT,
    js=ANIMATION_JS,
    width=400,
    height=400)
